  "context_summary": "36-year-old woman reports 12 days of nasal congestion and thick discharge. She felt like she was starting to improve around day 6, then got noticeably worse again over the last two days, with new pressure over her cheeks. No fever currently. The doctor is deciding whether this is a prolonged but self-limited viral rhinosinusitis or acute bacterial rhinosinusitis warranting antibiotics.",
  "good_next_question": "Had you started to feel better at some point and then gotten worse again, and are you noticing any new pressure over your cheeks or pain in your upper teeth?",
  "rationale": "The accepted clinical criteria for distinguishing acute bacterial rhinosinusitis from a prolonged viral URI are symptoms persisting beyond 10 days without improvement, or a biphasic 'double-sickening' pattern of initial improvement followed by worsening — both of which point to secondary bacterial infection rather than a slowly resolving viral process. New facial pressure over the maxillary sinuses or maxillary tooth pain adds specificity, since involvement of the sinus walls and floor is more consistent with bacterial sinusitis than simple viral congestion. This question directly targets the two validated criteria that shift management from supportive care to antibiotics, and is more discriminating than asking about congestion severity alone, which doesn't reliably separate viral from bacterial causes.",
